Reasoning: Paper 469066, "Lpd depletion reveals that SRF specifies radial versus tangential migration of pyramidal neurons," provides strong evidence supporting the claim. Specifically, proposition prop_626 states that "SRF is a transcription factor regulated by changes in the ratio of polymerized to unpolymerized actin." The abstract of the same paper further explains that "Lpd depletion caused bipolar pyramidal neurons to adopt a tangential, rather than radial-glial, migration mode... Mechanistically, Lpd depletion reduced the activity of SRF... Therefore, Lpd depletion exposes a role for SRF in directing pyramidal neurons to select a radial migration pathway along glia rather than a tangential migration mode." This directly links the balance between polymerized and unpolymerized actin (analogous to F-actin and G-actin) to the regulation of neuronal migration orientation (radial versus tangential) in pyramidal neurons during corticogenesis, which occurs in the developing cerebral cortex. The paper clearly demonstrates a mechanism by which actin dynamics influence the direction of neuronal movement.
